	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Maximising socio-economic benefits for ACP fisheries communities</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 January 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Differences between the ACP and the EU were aired at a major conference entitled 'ACP-EU fisheries relations - maximising socio-economic benefits for the ACP fisheries communities' held in Brussels from December 13th to 14th 2004. 140 representatives and fisheries experts from ACP countries met with the EC and various European professional organisations and NGOs. The meeting, designed to promote an exchange of information and points of view, was organised by the CTA, the Commonwealth Secretariat and the ACP Secretariat, as a follow up to a seminar held in April 2003.</p><p> The EC argued that FPAs aim to contribute to responsible fishing in the mutual interest of the parties concerned, ensuring both that the interests of the EU distant-water fleet are protected and that the conditions necessary to achieve sustainable fisheries in the waters of the partner concerned are strengthened.</p><p> ACP representatives questioned whether there were any substantive differences between the FPAs being proposed and the old bilateral access agreements. They highlighted the advantages of negotiating with the EU on a regional basis, as such an approach could reduce the power asymmetries that exist in bilateral negotiations between small ACP countries and the EU. In this regard, COMESA presented a proposal for a Fisheries Framework Agreement (FFA).</p><p> Other issues discussed included:</p>
<ul>

<li>IUU fishing (along with the various regional, national, and private efforts to stem illegal fishing); </li>

<li>non-tariff barriers, possibly deriving from SPS regulations; </li>

<li>the application of rules of origin, and various other aspects of market access; </li>

<li>the issue of how artisanal fishing should be defined. </li>

</ul>
<p> On the last point, it was felt that there was a need for clearer definitions as calls are being made in the WTO for artisanal fisheries to be exempt from disciplines on fisheries subsidies, and for developing countries to receive 'special and differential treatment'. This would be in line with the proposal to permit subsidies that promote sustainable development, whilst prohibiting all other subsidies that benefit the fishing industry and contribute directly to overcapacity and overfishing.</p><p> The day after the conference, the EC published a communication on 'Perspectives for simplifying and improving the regulatory environment of the Common Fisheries Policy' (see the later news item under this head) which showed some flexibility in relation to a regional approach to negotiations.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.cta.int/events2004/fish/index.htm" target="_self">Report on the expert meeting 'ACP-EU fisheries relations - maximising so...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/biores/04-12-20/story2.htm" target="_self">ICTSD, <i>BRIDGES, Trade Biores</i>, Vol. 4, No. 23, December 20th 2004</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/eur-lex/lex/LexUriServ/site/en/com/2004/com2004_0820en01.pdf" target="_self">Communication from the EC on 'Perspectives for simplifying and improving...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The seminar identified a number of areas of 'potential difficulties' for future ACP-EU FPA negotiations. These include the basis of the partnership itself and the IUU issue.</p><p> On the first, there is still a lack of understanding about the concrete differences between the 'new approach' being promoted by the EU through FPAs, and the former approach adopted in negotiating fishery-access agreements. One of the main driving forces behind the EC proposal seems to be the need to make EU fishery-access agreements compatible with WTO rules. It therefore remains to be seen whether this so-called 'new approach' will go further than a superficial 'white-washing' exercise.</p><p> Interestingly, even if it hardly featured in the meeting, one area where progress could be achieved is the adoption of a regional approach to EU-ACP negotiations. From the ACP side, a proposal was made for adopting a regionally harmonised framework for the negotiation of bilateral fisheries partnerships. This may be the best option for ACP countries, as compared to a full-blown regional FPA with several ACP countries, given the limited capacity of regional organisations. It may also be worth inviting the participation of professional organisations in the negotiations, particularly ones from the small-scale sector. This is likely to be easier to organise at the national rather than the regional level.</p><p> The EU response to a proposal for a regional approach was that they had no mandate to negotiate at regional level. However, there were some signs in the EC's communication on the Common Fisheries Policy the day after the seminar that there may be some scope for a regional approach to negotiations.</p><p> On the issue of IUU fishing it was widely agreed that it represents a threat to sustainable fisheries and requires greater cooperation at the regional level. But it seems that EU institutions and operators see the fight against IUU fishing more in terms of eliminating unfair competition from other distant-water fleets not abiding by the same rules. This is fair enough if the EU also takes seriously its responsibility to fight all IUU fishing. In this regard, the issue of the port of Las Palmas in the Canary Islands, a well-known centre of IUU fishing activities and an entry point to the EU market for illegally caught fish products, was raised, but with no response forthcoming from the EC.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
